Rating: 4
Truly a wonderful springboard for creative cooking! I made this yesterday for Mother's Day, and it was a terrific hit. My wife says it is better than Johnny Carino's (which is currently the best chain restaurant to get this dish, in my opinion). It was similar to Carino's, but with slightly thinner sauce. Also, Carino's doesn't include cream in their sauce, and this sauce (despite the cream) is a bit lighter and definitely less greasy. I did change a few things. I live in a small town, and the local package store only had sweet Marsala (Cribari 2007). It was quite good, though I can see the dry would be wonderful. I did taste the wine, and it seemed a bit cloyingly sweet for drinking alone. I used powdered rosemary instead of sage (I think I ended up using about 1 1/2 tsp total). I used half and half instead of cream, and I doubled the sauce and mushrooms (plus about oz extra mushrooms, for a total of 24 oz, and I added a little extra half and half as well). I did not cook ALL the water off from the mushrooms. The few ounces of broth made a nice addition to the sauce. The extra sauce made enough to have generous portions of sauce over fettuccine, and left over about 2 servings of sauce. I did not add extra Marsala at the end, because my wife is pregnant and my in-laws (who ate with us) abstain from alcohol for religious reasons. I simply added it all at the beginning so as to cook all the alcohol off. I added arrowroot starch to thicken the sauce, but it still could have been thicker (it ended up with a consistency like heavy cream). I used a lot of liquid with doubling the sauce, so I would recommend using an additional thickener if you double the sauce. All in all, it comes together nicely. It's an excellent, excellent recipe to use as a baseline from which to explore your inner gourmet. We will doubtless be having it again.

